m/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f76d17976d6b2c69167c10a1a18ad57e365c59be.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/40b20273217e1b18c59bbcd3f48b6ecca758706c.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/ed778e8997d71cec69276a0a32dbb603eb48ffc9.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/45a3d4a0cf7fba317fc285700037318d60dfa27d.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0f1453d113f15d43bcedff19610229a7f75ebf60.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6708d8959440b8805afc8470858dfedc048bcaa7.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5a0098f13086eababf4f3999ed7201d14098ef6a.jpeg"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" is the new entity  Priority : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/475d2c58c37e8bc97dca9aad347c0c4ad3232fd1.png]\nDescription: The image displays a hierarchical structure within a Model Browser interface for an application named \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The structure includes headings such as \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022Constants,\u0022 \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 and \u0022Database Data Types.\u0022 Under \u0022Entities,\u0022 the subfolder \u0022myapplication\u0022 is highlighted, specifically showing the \u0022Priority\u0022 section marked in red. Below \u0022Priority,\u0022 there are additional entries for \u0022_Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Organization Management,\u0022 \u0022Partner Management,\u0022 \u0022Resource Management,\u0022 and \u0022Root Menu.\u0022 The apparent purpose of the interface is to allow users to navigate and manage different elements and entities within the application\u0027s data model.\n\n\n  \n Git can also show you changes, as can TortoiseGit. \n \n \nGitBash \n In GitBash, simply enter this command: \n  git status\n  \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8572c5f02dbaf88980bf934d0f6c0424a242f667.png]\nDescription: The image displays a terminal interface from a Git command line session. The user, identified as \u0022Viktor,\u0022 navigates to the directory \u0060c/OrigamProjects/MyApplication\u0060 and performs various Git commands. Key outputs include the command \u0060git log\u0060, showing the latest commit with hash \u00601bb3684a202aef949143e0b7fe2419c34f027a\u0060, dated January 16, 2025. The commit message reads \u0022Initial commit.\u0022 Following this, the user executes \u0060git status\u0060, revealing that they are on the branch \u0022master\u0022 and noting that there are untracked files, including \u0060model/index.bin\u0060 and changes waiting to be committed. Instructions are provided for staging files with \u0060git add \u003Cfile\u003E\u0060 or restoring changes with \u0060git restore \u003Cfile\u003E\u0060. The interface and commands illustrate the process of tracking changes and managing files in a version control system.\n\n\n  \n This command will give you an overview of the files changed since the last version. You\u2019ll be able to see anything that was added, deleted, or modified. \n \n \n \nTortoiseGit \n In TortoiseGit, use the  Diff  option, which will display changes like this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/d/dbfc8f5b715b70e130ab53cb866fd690fe9d75a4.png]\nDescription: The image displays a TortoiseGit interface in a working tree context for a project located at \u0022C:\\OrigamProjects\\MyApplication.\u0022 It shows two file entries with the following details: \u0022model/index.bin\u0022 with an extension of .bin, status marked as \u0022Modified,\u0022 and \u0022model/myapplication/DataEntity/myapplication/Priority.origram\u0022 with an extension of .origram and status \u0022Added.\u0022 The columns include \u0022Lines added\u0022 with 40728, \u0022Lines removed\u0022 with 40673, and \u0022Last Modified\u0022 timestamps indicating 1/16/2025 at 1:35:13 PM for both files. The interface includes checkboxes for options like \u0022Show unversioned files,\u0022 \u0022Show ignore local changes flagged files,\u0022 \u0022Show ignored files,\u0022 and \u0022Show all staged files,\u0022 as well as buttons for \u0022Save unified diff,\u0022 \u0022Stash,\u0022 \u0022Commit,\u0022 \u0022Refresh,\u0022 and \u0022OK.\u0022 Below the file list, a summary line provides a count of lines and file statuses.\n\n\n  \n \n   Saving new versions \n Whenever you make significant updates or simply feel the need, you can save a new version of your application with Git. This will serve as an anchor point, allowing you to return to it if needed. \n \n \nGitBash \n  git add .\n  \n This command will add all changes to the new version. Then, create a new commit with those changes: \n  git commit -m \u0022Version with added entities\u0022\n  \n The text in quotes is your comment on the version, which helps distinguish between different versions and commits. In a real-world scenario, this could correspond to a new published version of your application or a specific development sprint. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/185aba8e47a1d73575862869f8dd0c602eebe6b3.png]\nDescription: The image displays a terminal window featuring a Git command session. The user, identified as \u0022victor@HP-book-Viktor,\u0022 is working within the directory \u0022c/OrigamProjects/MyApplication\u0022 on the master branch. The commands executed include \u0022git add .","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:39:11"},"vector":[-0.025601607,-0.027826032,-0.034560714,0.038047675,-0.0028036158,-0.06238065,0.004587334,0.0013326051,-0.007630679,0.03171056,0.0034171194,-0.0434501,-0.008418714,0.041718617,0.0049392106,0.00014067636,0.009294837,0.031343725,0.003882771,0.0047188257,-0.0012486645,-0.008371745,0.053579293,0.010009515,0.0067837187,0.03498879,0.034650892,-0.0218